Scenarios
Scenario 1 — Complete Focus Session, Earn Points, and Level Up
The student starts a 25-minute focus timer. The TimerController creates a FocusSession and begins ticking every second, emitting the countdown via StateFlow to the UI. When the timer reaches zero, FocusSession.end(completed=true) is called. PointsManager calculates points = (25 * 10) * bonusMultiplier(1.2) = 300. User.addPoints(300) brings totalPoints to 1250, which triggers a level-up check. VirtualHome.loadLayout(Level2) is called and the session is saved to SessionRepository. The UI displays "+300 points! Level 2 Unlocked!".
This validates: TimerController, FocusSession, PointsManager, User, VirtualHome, MVVM state flow, IO thread save

Scenario 2 — Distraction Detected During Session
The student starts a focus session and switches to Instagram. Every minute, TimerController queries UsageStatsManager.getCurrentForegroundApp(), which returns "com.instagram.android". A DistractionEvent is created and passed to FocusSession.recordDistraction(), incrementing distractionCount. The event is saved to SessionRepository asynchronously so the timer is not interrupted. TimerScreen.showWarning("Stay focused!") is called and the student sees a banner. When the session ends, completionRate = 0.75 due to distractions, and the result is displayed.
This validates: distraction detection loop, DistractionEvent, async repository save, UI warning, completion rate calculation

Scenario 3 — App Killed Mid-Session (Crash Recovery)
The student has a focus session running with 10 minutes left. Android kills the process due to low memory. The app had previously saved remainingSeconds=600, isRunning=true, and sessionId to SharedPreferences. When the student reopens the app, TimerViewModel.checkForIncompleteSession() finds a session with isCompleted=false in SessionRepository and shows a resume dialog. If the student taps Resume, resumeTimer(remainingSeconds=600) restores the session and the timer continues from 10:00. If the student taps Discard, FocusSession.markAsAbandoned() is called and a new session can begin.
This validates: SharedPreferences crash recovery, SessionRepository query, TimerController resume, FocusSession state

Scenario 4 — Level Up and Unlock Home Items
After earning enough points, Level.isUnlocked(1250) checks requiredPoints=1000 and returns true. User.levelUp() calls getNextLevel(1) returning Level 2. VirtualHome.loadLayout(Level2) updates activeLayoutId to "home_level2". getUnlockedItemsForLevel(2) returns [Tree, Fountain] and adds them to unlockedItems. A levelUpEvent is emitted to the UI, which calls showLevelUpAnimation() and renderNewItems([Tree, Fountain]). The student sees "Level 2! New items unlocked!" and can place items in the home.
This validates: User, Level, VirtualHome, HomeLayout, HomeItem, UI event emission, MVVM event flow

Scenario 5 — Challenge Progress and Completion
When a session completes, PointsManager.sessionCompleted(session) calls ChallengeRepository.getActiveChallenges(). For each active challenge, Challenge.updateProgress(session.duration) is called, which internally calls ChallengeEvaluator.evaluate(userId) returning progress=0.85. If progress reaches 1.0, checkCompletion() returns true, calculateChallengePoints() returns bonusPoints=500, User.addPoints(500) is called, isCompleted=true is set, and the challenge is saved. The student is notified of the 500 bonus points. If progress is below 1.0, only the progress value is saved and no points are awarded yet.
This validates: Strategy Pattern, ChallengeEvaluator, PointsManager, ChallengeRepository, challenge loop logic

Scenario 6 — Weekly Report Generation
At Sunday 23:59, WorkManager triggers WeeklyReportWorker.doWork(). AnalyticsAggregator.generateWeeklyReport() queries AppUsageStat and FocusSession for the last 7 days in parallel. AnalyticsReport.generate() calculates: completion rate, total focus minutes, top distracting apps, average session length, and longest streak. The report is saved to Room. If the user opted in for notifications, NotificationManager.showNotification() shows "Weekly report ready". Otherwise, the report is saved silently. WorkManager.Result.success() is returned.
This validates: WorkManager scheduling, AnalyticsAggregator, parallel queries, AnalyticsReport, NotificationManager, opt-in logic

10. Size and Performance
The Gamified Focus System is designed for individual student use on a single Android device. It is not designed for multi-user or server-scale operation.
Expected Size

Single user per device installation
Hundreds of focus sessions stored over weeks or months
Small reference datasets for levels, challenges, and home items
Per-session distraction events stored locally

Performance Characteristics

Timer runs on Default Dispatcher — UI thread is never blocked
Room database operations run on IO Dispatcher — no ANR risk
Distraction event saves are asynchronous — timer accuracy is maintained
Weekly report uses parallel queries for AppUsageStat and FocusSession
WorkManager handles background work in a doze-safe manner
StateFlow keeps UI reactive and updates only when state actually changes

Limitations

No cloud sync across devices
No caching layer beyond Room
No load balancing or distributed infrastructure
Single-user, single-device assumptions
UsageStatsManager requires explicit user permission grant

These tradeoffs are acceptable for the current project scope.

11. Quality
Maintainability
The system uses a strict MVVM layered architecture where each layer has a single clear responsibility. Adding a new screen, data type, or feature requires changes only in the relevant layer without affecting others.
Modifiability
New challenge types can be added by creating a new ChallengeEvaluator implementation without modifying the Challenge class or any existing evaluators. New home items and levels can be added through data alone.
Usability
The system provides direct flows for all core student actions:

Start, pause, and resume a focus session
View and interact with the virtual home
Browse and track challenges
View the analytics dashboard
Resume an interrupted session after a crash

Security

All data is stored locally on the device
No user credentials are transmitted
Cloud export (optional) sends only anonymized data
UsageStatsManager access requires explicit user permission

Reliability
The system uses crash recovery via SharedPreferences, structured validation in all repositories, asynchronous database writes to prevent data loss, and WorkManager for reliable background job execution that survives device restarts.
Simplicity
The architecture avoids unnecessary complexity such as multi-user support, cloud sync, chat systems, and external API dependencies. This keeps the system focused and appropriate for an academic software engineering project.

12. Appendices
Acronyms and Abbreviations

MVVM: Model-View-ViewModel
DAO: Data Access Object
IPC: Inter-Process Communication
API: Application Programming Interface
DB: Database
OCP: Open/Closed Principle
UI: User Interface
ANR: Application Not Responding

Definitions

Focus Session: A timed period during which the student commits to studying without distractions
Distraction Event: A recorded instance where the student switched to a distracting app during a session
Challenge: A goal the student works toward over multiple sessions (e.g. complete 5 sessions in a week)
ChallengeEvaluator: A strategy class that calculates progress for a specific challenge type
Virtual Home: A visual space that the student customizes by placing unlocked items earned through leveling up
Level: A progression milestone unlocked when the student accumulates enough total points
PointsManager: The component responsible for calculating how many points a session is worth
WorkManager: Android's API for scheduling reliable background tasks that survive process death and device restarts

Design Principles Applied

Separation of Concerns — UI, business logic, and data are in distinct layers
Single Responsibility Principle — each class has one clear job
Open/Closed Principle — Challenge system is open for extension via new evaluators, closed for modification
Strategy Pattern — ChallengeEvaluator interface allows pluggable challenge logic
Observer Pattern — Kotlin Flow and StateFlow provide reactive, unidirectional data flow
Repository Pattern — all data access goes through repositories; ViewModels never touch DAOs directly
Offline-First Design — all core features work without internet access
Low Coupling, High Cohesion — layers interact only through defined interfaces
